<td><FONT SIZE="1" FACE="Tahoma, Arial, Helvetica" COLOR="#000040">Originally posted by Surutca Eagleeye on 01-06-2000 07:59 AM<BR></FONT>
<TEXTAREA NAME="EditedMessage" ROWS=10 COLS=45 WRAP="VIRTUAL">Sorry to start these up again but I just have to know  :)

I therefore bumb to postings I have made deep down under other topics:

FIRST POSTING

Some of the perhaps many unknowns we need to investigate to understand actual weapon damage over time is:

(a) how str bonus is calculated.

Do you get the same bonus on any weapon? 2H or 1H, high or low dmg weapon?

I have to go home to check this one 

And how exactly does it relate to your str?

(b) how your below max hits are calculated

If its fixed numbers as assumed in the 3 dmg example above then it favors the faster 1H weapons all other things being equal. If its percentages of the normal max damage it dosent matter.

(c) how critical hits are calculated

I assume its 2 x base dmg (before str bonus) + str bonus.

As opposed to 2 x (base dmg +str bonus)

Your maximum base dmg being 2 x the weapon damage.


Actually we should be able to figure these things out if we just collect diffent players dmg figures at different levels with different weapons and str stats. The only problem is that you normally dont play enough different combos yourself at any given level to figure it out.

Surutca Eagleeye

SECOND POSTING

Come on you high level guys. You can do better than this  simulation and magic number crap.

All we need to know is:

(a) Is the str bonus a fixed number or a percentage of the weapon dmg (or some combo formula).

If its a fixed number the simple dmg/dly ratio will tend to favor the higher dmg 2H when compared to actual in game damage at higher levels.

If its a percentage the simple dmg/dly should be ok.

This can not be very hard to find out for all you high str warriors with weapons of both types 

(b) Is lower than max hits a percentage of your ordinary hits (before or after str nonus) or fixed low numbers (or a combo formula)?

If its a straight percentage the in game feeling that dual 1H is better than 2H at higher levels has NOTHING to do with the average hit vs max hit argument.


I will be waiting for the answers 

BTW from a mathematical point of wiev there is nothing strange in the fact that dual 1H gets better and better compared to 2H as you raise in levels because of the simple fact that when you use dual 1H there is 2 percentage increases that raise as you level (chance for dubble attack and chance of dual) whereas the 2H warrior only get one percentage increase (chance for dubble attack) not to mention the chance of dubble dual  Therefore the damage courves of a dual 1H warrior will raise faster than that of a 2H warrior and most likely pass it if we for the sake of argument assume that they both stick to 1 weapon throughout their life. It could for that matter be Dual FS longswords vs. FS 2Hander.

Therefore if we assume that the simple dmg/dly gap between 1H and 2H is the same for all levels of weapons dual 1H will catch up to 2H. Whether or not it passes depends on the actual dmg/dly difference and thus on the available weapon selection in game.

Surutca Eagleeye


</TEXTAREA>
